article.description: Penny Taylor scored 20 points and Diana Taurasi added 17 to lead the Phoenix Mercury to a 69-65 victory at Minnesota on Friday night.
article.headline: Taylor, Taurasi lead Phoenix to third straight win
article.linkText: Visiting Mercury corral Lynx, win 7 of last 8 games
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The Phoenix Mercury hope their late,
come-from-behind victory is just the start of what is yet to come.

Penny Taylor scored 20 points, including four free throws in the
final 35.8 seconds, as the Mercury overcame a 16-point deficit for
a 69-65 victory Friday night over the Minnesota Lynx.

The Mercury (10-12) started the season with three wins in their
first 14 games, but they recovered to win seven of eight. After a
game at Detroit on Sunday, they play seven of their next eight at
home as they fight for the final playoff spot in the Western
Conference.

"We always knew it was going to be tough with the schedule we
had at the start and with the absence of players," said Phoenix
coach Carrie Graf, whose team added forward Maria Stepanova and
center Kamila Vodichkova more than a month into the season.

"Our aim was to try to keep our head above water," Graf added.
"Unfortunately, our head was under water. But we went blue in the
face, we came up for air and we're going OK now. We've learned to
swim."

Diana Taurasi added 17 for the Mercury, and hit the biggest
basket of the night, a 3-pointer from the top of the key that tied
the game at 65 with 1:45 to play.

"It was a shot that we needed to make, and it was up to me to
make it this time, so it felt good," Taurasi said. "I've been
comfortable since second grade making shots like that. That's what
you practice for."

Stepanova had 14 points while Vodichkova added 10 rebounds for
the Mercury, who won despite shooting just 41 percent from the
field and falling behind 37-21 late in the first half.

"Pretty much the whole game we played like garbage," Taurasi
said, "but in the end we found a way to get a couple of shots and
a couple of rebounds to go down. That's just a credit to everybody
on this team to stay with the focus on team play."

Svetlana Abrosimova led the Lynx with 20 points and Amber Jacobs
had 10 for Minnesota, which has lost three straight. Minnesota shot
52 percent from the floor, but committed 20 turnovers and missed
nine of 17 free throws.

"Do we have what it takes to be a playoff team? Absolutely,"
Lynx coach Suzie McConnell Serio said. "Did we show it tonight?
No."

After Taurasi's big basket, Taylor made two free throws with
35.8 seconds remaining to give the Mercury their first lead.

Minnesota's Katie Smith failed to hit the rim on a driving shot
on the final Lynx possession, and the shot clock ran out before
Minnesota could attempt another shot. Taylor made two more free
throws with three seconds left to seal the victory.

"I got a sense that nobody wanted to take the last shot, and we
can't win like that," McConnell Serio said.

Jacobs and Abrosimova each hit a pair of 3-pointers in a 14-2
run to help the Lynx take a 37-21 lead with 4:53 to play.

But Phoenix scored 12 of the final 14 points in the half, with
Stepanova converting a low-post move in the final minute to bring
the Mercury to within 39-33 at the break.

The Mercury have won consecutive games against the two teams --
Los Angeles and Minnesota -- in the race for fourth place in the
West.

"We want to give them a great push," Graf said, "and we
believe the win over L.A. and the win here tonight were monumental
in doing that."
